You want to achieve this using Webpack and ensure that the resulting library-like file includes all dependencies, styles, and templates.

To achieve this goal, you can modify your Webpack configuration and utilize the `html-webpack-inline-source-plugin` to embed the HTML templates directly into your final JavaScript file. This approach will create a self-contained library that can be easily included in other HTML files. Here's how you can achieve this:

1. Install the necessary plugins:

```bash
npm install html-webpack-inline-source-plugin --save-dev
```

2. Update your Webpack configuration to use the `html-webpack-inline-source-plugin`:

```javascript
const HtmlWebpackPlugin = require('html-webpack-plugin');
const MiniCssExtractPlugin = require('mini-css-extract-plugin');
const HtmlWebpackInlineSourcePlugin = require('html-webpack-inline-source-plugin');
const TerserPlugin = require('terser-webpack-plugin');
const path = require('path');

const config = {
  // ... your existing configuration ...

  plugins: [
    // ... your existing plugins ...

    new HtmlWebpackPlugin({
      // ... your existing HtmlWebpackPlugin options ...
      templateParameters: {
        initConsoleLog: 'MMWrapper start',
        __INLINE_SOURCE__: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      },
      inlineSource: '.(js|css)$' // This will inline the sources
    }),

    // ... your existing plugins ...

    new MiniCssExtractPlugin({
      // ... your existing MiniCssExtractPlugin options ...
    }),

    new HtmlWebpackInlineSourcePlugin() // Add this plugin
  ]
};

module.exports = config;
```

3. Modify your entry HTML templates (e.g., `src/html/xmg_mm_wrapper_template.ejs`) to conditionally include the styles and scripts when `__INLINE_SOURCE__` is true:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <% if (__INLINE_SOURCE__) { %>
      <style><%= require('./css/xmg/marketing_base.css') %></style>
      <script><%= require('./modules/xmg_mm_wrapper_bottom_banner.js') %></script>
    <% } %>
    <!-- Rest of your head content -->
  </head>
  <body>
    <!-- ... -->
  </body>
</html>
```

4. Build your library-like file:

```bash
NODE_ENV=production webpack
```

This approach will result in a single JavaScript file that contains the HTML, styles, and scripts. You can attach this library-like file to another HTML file, and it will load its own HTML, styles, and logic.

