I'm going to investigate how this could be fixed, but any hint from the maintainers would be very much appreciated.

I thought one way to fix it could probably be using `Proxy` or pseudo proxies (like webpack does internally, using getters) instead of `var`s. Like this:

```javascript
var __webpack_exports__event = new Proxy(__webpack_exports__.event);
var __webpack_exports__setEvent = new Proxy(__webpack_exports__.setEvent);
export { __webpack_exports__event as event, __webpack_exports__setEvent as setEvent };
```

But I would like to hear opinions on this approach, since it could have side effects that I don't foresee.

I've been doing some experiments in [ModuleLibraryPlugin](https://github.com/webpack/webpack/blob/1f13ff9fe587e094df59d660b4611b1bd19aed4c/lib/library/ModuleLibraryPlugin.js) trying to fix this issue and have realized that it is impossible :-/ (unless someone else comes with better ideas than mine, of course).

What I've tried is using `Proxy` in the hope to defer the evaluation of exports until the very point where they are used. In other words, webpack defines dynamic getters for all its internal exports, like this:

```javascript
/* harmony export */ __webpack_require__.d(__webpack_exports__, {
/* harmony export */   event: () => (/* binding */ event),
/* harmony export */   setEvent: () => (/* binding */ setEvent)
/* harmony export */ });
```
(where `__webpack_require__.d` is akin to doing `Object.defineProperty(name, getter)`)

So whenever the code accesses `event` in a module that imports it, the getter is being executed. This makes possible exporting module internal variable as bindings that are "updated" every time the internal variable changes its value (like `var event` in the example).

However, the ESM export code breaks this binding, as said above:

```javascript
var __webpack_exports__event = __webpack_exports__.event;
var __webpack_exports__setEvent = __webpack_exports__.setEvent;
export { __webpack_exports__event as event, __webpack_exports__setEvent as setEvent };
```

The first line is invoking the getter to assign the resulted value to `__webpack_exports__event` but once it is assigned, the binding is broken and the exports is no longer bound to the exported `var event`. Thus it will remain `null` forever.

What I tried first is exporting proxies, like this:

```javascript
var __webpack_exports__event = new Proxy(__webpack_exports__.event, {});
var __webpack_exports__setEvent = new Proxy(__webpack_exports__.setEvent, {});
export { __webpack_exports__event as event, __webpack_exports__setEvent as setEvent };
```

However, that fails, because line 1 invokes the getter to create the `Proxy` and, since it returns `null` on first place, the `Proxy` constructor complains.

So, I tried this:

```javascript
var __webpack_exports__event = new Proxy(
	{}, 
	{
		apply() {return Reflect.apply(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		construct() {return Reflect.construct(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		defineProperty() {return Reflect.defineProperty(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		deleteProperty() {return Reflect.deleteProperty(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		get() {return Reflect.get(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		getOwnPropertyDescriptor() {return Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		getPrototypeOf() {return Reflect.getPrototypeOf(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		has() {return Reflect.has(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		isExtensible() {return Reflect.isExtensible(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		ownKeys() {return Reflect.ownKeys(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		preventExtensions() {return Reflect.preventExtensions(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		set() {return Reflect.set(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
		setPrototypeOf() {return Reflect.setPrototypeOf(__webpack_exports__.event, ...arguments.slice(1));},
	}
);
```

Which would have worked and (maybe) led us to a disaster thinking that I had fixed it. However, I was lucky and it failed because `event`'s initial value was `null` (again). Had it been other thing like `{}`, for example, it would have seemed to work.

Why is that?

Well, it turns out that when you use a proxy, you can intercept/substitute every access to the proxied object except for the evaluation of the value of the object itself. This is because `null` is special in the sense that `null` is not an object that has null value, but `null` itself.

In other words, if you export a proxy as `event`, it will never be `null` when imported, because it's in fact an object. Conversely, if you export `null` as `event` it will be null forever, there's no way you can change its value then.

Conclusion: we cannot fix webpack to make the example I provided behave like pure ECMAScript due to limitations in the language, which means that if we wanted to make the example work under a webpack scenario we would have to modify the example, not webpack :-(. 

